.TH ESH 1 "March, 2026"

.SH NAME
\fBesh\fP \- The Experimental SHell.

.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBesh\fP \fIscript\fP [\fIargs\fP]...
.br
\fBesh\fP \fB\-c\fP \fIcmd\fP

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBEsh\fP is the default shell in ToaruOS until you install one that's actually good.
.PP
\fBEsh\fP is not a POSIX shell, or anything remotely resembling one.
.PP
An initial build of ToaruOS ships with \fB/bin/sh\fP symlinked to \fB/bin/esh\fP to
allow
.IR system (3)
to work correctly.
.PP
It is not recommended that users put any effort into actually using \fBEsh\fP.
For a real programming environment, use
.IR kuroko (1)
instead. For a real shell,
.IR dash (1)
is available from the package repository.

.TP
.B \-c \fIcmd\fP
Execute the shell command provided in the argument.

.SH SYNTAX
\fBEsh\fP parses its input line by line, token by token, and does not support any
complex syntactic constructs.
.PP
Conditionals and loops like \fBif\fP and \fBwhile\fP are implemnted as simple commands.
Because these commands generally only accept a single "subcommand", and not a full body
with a sequence of commands, if you wish to perform more complicated tasks within the
body (or conditional) of one of these constructs, you should use a subshell like
\fBesh \-c "cmd; cmd; cmd"\fP as the body.

.TP
.B if
Conditionally execute a command based on the result of another command.
.sp
\fBif\fP \fIcondition_command\fP... \fBthen\fP \fItrue_command\fP... [\fBelse\fP \fIfalse_command\fP...]
.sp
The \fBif\fP command will execute \fIcondition_command\fP. If the exit status is 0,
it will then execute \fItrue_command\fP. Otherwise, if a \fIfalse_command\fP was provided,
it will be executed instead.
.sp
The final return status of the \fBif\fP command is the exit
status of whichever of the \fItrue_command\fP or \fIfalse_command\fP is executed,
or 0 if the "else" branch was taken but no \fIfalse_command\fP was provided.

.TP
.B while
Conditionally execute a command in a loop, based on the result of another command.
.sp
\fBwhile\fP \fIcondition_command\fP... \fBdo\fP \fIbody_command\fP...
.sp
The \fBwhile\fP command parses its arguments to find a \fBdo\fP to determine
the boundaries of \fIcondition_command\fP and \fIbody_command\fP. It will then
repeatedly run \fIcondition_command\fP, check for a 0 return code, and then
execute \fIbody_command\fP. If \fIcondition_command\fP has a non-0 exit status,
the loop terminates.
.sp
The final return status of the \fBwhile\fP command is the exit status of the
the last \fIcondition_command\fP that was non-0.
.sp
The \fBwhile\fP command will also try to handle disruptive signals during
execution of \fIbody_command\fP.

.TP
.B not
Return the boolean inverse of the exit status of a subcommand.
.sp
\fBnot\fP \fIcondition_command\fP...
.sp
The \fBnot\fP command will execute a \fIcondition_command\fP and then return the boolean
inverse of its exit status. Eg., if the command returned non-0, \fBnot\fP will return 0,
and if the command returned 0, \fBnot\fP will return 1.

.TP
.B export\-cmd
.sp
\fBexport\-cmd\fP \fIvar\fP \fIcommand\fP...
.sp
Runs \fIcommand\fP with its standard output redirected to a pipe, and reads the pipe
to store the command's output in $\fIvar\fP. As of writing, this command only collects
up to 1023 bytes to place in the variable, and will then stop reading, but will still
wait for \fIcommand\fP to finish, which is probably not going to end well.

.SH NOTES
If you are unfortunate enough to need to write a complex shell script that works
with a clean installation of ToaruOS, be sure to use \fB/bin/esh\fP in the hash\-bang
and not \fB/bin/sh\fP as users are encouraged to replace that symlink with one
pointing to a real shell as soon as they have one.

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR kuroko (1)

